<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/643252-do-i-need-to-read-the-other-2-proceeding">Do I need to read the other 2 proceeding books first?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_643252'><a id="like_count_community_question_643252" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/643252?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">14 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F19494.The_Spy_Who_Came_In_from_the_Cold">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/643252-do-i-need-to-read-the-other-2-proceeding">6 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/643252-do-i-need-to-read-the-other-2-proceeding">See all 4 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/2794271-stephen-sanders"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1396800915i/2794271._UY100_CR16,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/2794271-stephen-sanders">Stephen Sanders</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">You don&apos;t have to. The events of his first book, Call for the Dead, are frequently referenced in the Spy Who Came in from the Cold, but are summarized<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">‚Ä¶more</a></span><span class="fullContent">You don't have to. The events of his first book, Call for the Dead, are frequently referenced in the Spy Who Came in from the Cold, but are summarized so you don't need to have read it. However, it's a solid mystery and a quick read so there's no reason not to read it first. It's also interesting to see how Le Carre's style evolved between the two books. <br /><br />Le Carre's second novel, A Murder of Quality, on the other hand, is a mediocre mystery novel with a plot that has no relation to this book. Definitely skip it. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

