        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3569014532" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4156858954584226084">I read this book shortly after it appeared, having the benefit of a mother who was an aficionado of every good book review she read in The New York Times or Kirkus Reviews, to both of which she subscribed. <br/><br/>With that advantage she also had been given free reign by town hall to order whatever book had stellar ratings and would consequently enjoy a big circulation in the library she ran for them.<br/><br/>Furthermore, if she loved a book she would tell me about it, and I&apos;d borrow it.<br/><br/>And that way I could read</span>
  <span id="freeText4156858954584226084" style="display:none">I read this book shortly after it appeared, having the benefit of a mother who was an aficionado of every good book review she read in The New York Times or Kirkus Reviews, to both of which she subscribed. <br /><br />With that advantage she also had been given free reign by town hall to order whatever book had stellar ratings and would consequently enjoy a big circulation in the library she ran for them.<br /><br />Furthermore, if she loved a book she would tell me about it, and I'd borrow it.<br /><br />And that way I could read great extracurricular books in my teen years at no cost...<br /><br />But my marks naturally suffered as a result!<br /><br />That year, when I turned thirteen, I abhorred George Smiley's Circus and its bitter sang froid with regards to the slightest touch of humanism. <br /><br />I was all teen emotion at the time, but later would naturally see the Circus' hidden humanity once le Carre's own humanism mellowed with age.<br /><br />Appreciation for workplace excellence will do that to you.<br /><br />You let down your guard with sheer admiration!<br /><br />So it was with President Kennedy in the previous year, as his finger hovered over the red nuclear button, like Peter Sellers in Dr Strangelove.<br /><br />The only great guts and glory I could see in such machismo at the time was the vision of what we'd all turn into AFTER it was pushed!<br /><br />Now, of course, much older, I only see Kennedy's sheer stamina and bravery -<br /><br />Just as I now know that for Alex Leamas, inhuman political expediency was a calculated risk back then, given the grim times.<br /><br />However, now with Coronavirus, careful and humane medical treatment in many areas is sadly lacking due to sheer volume of cases. <br /><br />Are we now, perhaps, finding ourselves once again in the crisis-averse deep waters of starkly expedient measures?</span>
  <a data-text-id="4156858954584226084" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


