<div id="review_4327564302" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4327564302" />
    <a title="Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26682058-scott"><img alt="Scott" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1642216579p2/26682058.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4327564302?book_show_action=true">Nov 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott" href="/user/show/26682058-scott">Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780553225587" href="/book/show/1933020.The_Spy_Who_Came_in_from_the_Cold">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4327564302" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10352476445968380210"><i>&quot;What do you think spies are - priests, saints or martyrs? They&apos;re a squalid procession of vain fools, traitors too, yes; pansies, sadists and drunkards, people who play &apos;cowboys and Indians&apos; to brighten their rotten lives. Do you think they sit like monks, balancing the rights and wrongs?&quot;</i> -- bellicose protagonist Alec Leamas, a British intelligence operative, on page 214<br/><br/>I&apos;ve read that author le Carre had intentionally structured his spy-centered books from the early 60&apos;s in direct opposition t</span>
  <span id="freeText10352476445968380210" style="display:none"><i>"What do you think spies are - priests, saints or martyrs? They're a squalid procession of vain fools, traitors too, yes; pansies, sadists and drunkards, people who play 'cowboys and Indians' to brighten their rotten lives. Do you think they sit like monks, balancing the rights and wrongs?"</i> -- bellicose protagonist Alec Leamas, a British intelligence operative, on page 214<br /><br />I've read that author le Carre had intentionally structured his spy-centered books from the early 60's in direct opposition to (or, with his extreme dislike of) 'Bondmania,' as secret agent 007 was a steady presence on international bestseller lists <i>and</i> making inroads in the film world. Well, after reading <i>The Spy Who Came in From the Cold</i>, I think I'll stick with Ian Fleming's work - other than admittedly suspenseful first and final chapters, I found this slow-moving and just too talky. I'm also not sure it translates well to a 21st century audience, given that this was first published when the Cold War was still active and very much a hot topic. (However, lots of GR friends as well as other readers have given it high ratings, so opinions will vary.) Much of the text consisted of mostly men - the handful of involved characters uniformly came off as stiff, often spouting flat or humorless dialogue - sitting in a room together, conversing about persons / events that weren't particularly explained very well, making it like the reader was listening in on two complete strangers during a chat. It was boring in many stretches (and I get it - le Carre was going for some bitter realism here), and for a story only 200+ pages in length there were chunks of time I simply had no idea what the hell was going on. I'm glad other readers liked it a lot, but I was just puzzled by the fanfare attached to this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10352476445968380210" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

